1. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper proposes a new compressed representation of the LCP array, which is a fundamental data structure used in many string processing algorithms. 
2. cs.IR (Information Retrieval): The LCP array is used in many text indexing and search algorithms, which are relevant to information retrieval. 
3. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing): The paper discusses the time/space trade-offs of using the sampled LCP array with a compressed suffix array, which can be relevant to distributed and parallel computing. 
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity): The paper discusses the optimal time and space complexity of using the suffix array with the LCP array to solve string processing problems. 
5. cs.DL (Digital Libraries): The paper's focus on string processing and text indexing can be relevant to digital libraries and information management systems.
